<br>
At some point it all will average out. It doesn't matter what your weapon's delay is, you're counting hits vs crits and not crits per minute. It doesn't matter how much damage you're doing because you don't care how much damage the critical does, again, you're just trying to learn their frequency. The only relevant data would be those things that modify the <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> frequency</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> of criticals, such as dex. If your sample size is large enough, even dex would become less meaningful, but ought to still be noted for comparison to individual CF2 and CF3 logs.<br>
<br>
If after logging 2 million CF1 hits, 2 million CF2 hits, and 2 million CF3 hits, all from different people, same people, whatever... if after all that each of those sets of data says they're all scoring critical hits nearly 2% of the time... isn't that enough evidance to say, &quot;you know, it really DOES seem like a waste to put another 10 skill points into this.&quot; <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#2f2f4f><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub35.ezboard.com/utremainbladesinger.showPublicProfile?language=EN>TremainBladesinger</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#FF0000>(12/25/01 1:40:29 pm)</font><br>    <BR><img src=http://www.theunholytrinity.org/cracks_smileys/cwm/big/firemad.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Combat Fury -- Arguably Broken - Parsing Statistics Incl</span><hr size=1> You are wrong, if its not the same person with the same gear fighting the same mobs then your data is useless.  Level of the mob compared to yours makes a huge difference in how much you crit, among other things.  I'm sorry tilara but i dont see your point at all, if half of those people are fighting low levels mobs and getting crits 3% of the time and the other half are fighting uber mobs and criting 1% of the time the average will still be 2%, you are counting crits vs hits when there are so many more variables that can make a difference.<br>
